Liquid Staking
Layer-1

LSTs, Sanctum, and Stake-Weighted QoS
Dustin Teander
Seth Bloomberg

May 10, 2024 ⋅  5 min read

Primer

Beginning in Q4 2023 and throughout Q1 2024, Solana witnessed a surge in trading and memecoin activity.

New tokens were being created daily at a massive clip, with Solana, in particular, being the platform of choice for new token deployments. Towards the most recent peak of activity, in March 2024, over 150,000 new tokens were launched across a variety of chains, with Solana consistently accounting for well over half of these new tokens.

The memecoin mania naturally led to increased onchain activity, with users competing to ensure their transactions landed onchain as quickly as possible. As can be the case with any blockchain, increased onchain activity brings to light scalability concerns that are simply not present during lower volume periods. For Solana, the concerns are largely associated with the transaction processing pipeline.

Relative to Ethereum and other EVM implementations, Solana transaction prioritization and processing differs in numerous ways, most notably is the absence of a native mempool.

Processing a Solana transaction involves sending transactions through an RPC server, and then a validator processes them via the transaction scheduler. The congestion issues are localized to both areas, each with different solutions to solve.

  • Transaction Scheduler: Ideally, the transaction scheduler is responsible for ordering transactions and can sort them via a priority fee included by the user. However, the current implementation does not guarantee that the priority will be respected. Thus, it partially operates on a FIFO basis, which, in turn, is suspected of encouraging spam transactions.
  • Transaction Routing (RPC): Before transactions hit the validator’s transaction scheduler, they must pass through RPC nodes that connect to transaction processing nodes. During Solana’s congestion issues, the leader's (i.e., the current block builder) bandwidth becomes saturated. Additionally, priority fees at this layer are not recognized and are unable to aid priority routing. Emerging as the near-term practical solution has been staked weighted Quality of Service (swQoS), which enables the leader to allocate the majority of its bandwidth to staked connections. The “virtual stake” serves as a quality signal for the leader, helping it determine which connections to listen to.

The introduction of swQoS has direct implications for Solana’s application layer, as teams now are incentivized to accumulate SOL and issue liquid stake tokens (LSTs) against these deposits.

Analyst Insights

Dustin

While the swQoS solution has potential centralization concerns, it introduces a new structural demand for the SOL token and aligns incentives for apps built on the chain. In order to secure bandwidth for their users, applications on Solana are exploring launching their own LST token, which secures more priority bandwidth for transactions issued from their app. For example, Jupiter, regularly the largest DEX aggregator by volume, has launched jupSOL, which effectively enables Jupiter users to get priority access to Solana blockspace. So, if a protocol wants to secure a better UX for its users, they have a strong incentive to acquire SOL and launch its own LST.

However, the typical problem with launching an LST is both attracting enough deposits and then maintaining the peg against the underlying token, SOL, in this case. The first problem can be addressed with protocol loyalty or token rewards to offer higher staking returns on the staked SOL. The second problem is being addressed by Sanctum. Sanctum offers a multi-LST DEX pool called Infinity, which provides liquidity support for LSTs launched with Sanctum. So far, notable projects like Jupiter, Drift, and Bonk have launched LSTs with Sanctum to secure better UX for their users.

Apps being structural demand sinks for the ecosystem native token is new and unique to the Solana ecosystem. As demand to use an application like Jupiter increases, the more SOL Jupiter needs to attract to its LST to secure bandwidth, creating an incentive-aligned flywheel for SOL. The core risk, however, is network upgrades that shift the congestion bottleneck away from an emphasis on transaction routing and, thus, swQoS.

Seth

As Dustin noted, the swQoS system presents a compelling opportunity for Solana-based applications to accumulate SOL from its users. The more SOL an application amasses directly correlates with a better UX, an important competitive differentiator, especially for DeFi-focused applications.

Beyond the bandwidth benefits swQoS enables, each application can tailor its LST as needed. Consider Jupiter’s LST, jupSOL. As is the case with other LSTs, jupSOL accrues staking rewards from its corresponding staked SOL. In addition to the SOL staking rewards, jupSOL holders have the following benefits:

  • The Jupiter team has delegated an additional 100,000 SOL to its validator, leading to higher staking rewards for jupSOL holders.
  • All MEV rewards are funneled back to jupSOL holders. MEV rewards should naturally scale with general economic activity flowing through Jupiter.
  • There are no withdrawal fees and only a small 10 bps deposit fee.

For applications that are able to collect a large volume of SOL deposits, swQoS can create a new market and revenue opportunity for these applications that effectively become large aggregators of Solana’s network bandwidth. Some teams may look to auction off or sell access to their swQoS bandwidth. Given the relatively high economic barriers to entry with swQoS (i.e., 15,000 staked SOL amount, or ~$2.3 million), this may present a low-cost path for new DeFi teams to achieve similar UX that larger, more mature teams have established.
